Across the UAE, 81 percent of women, the highest rate among the five countries, expressed willingness to allow their female doctors access to abortion details – irrespective of confidentiality laws – as long as the doctor does it in good faith.

The sharpest differences in opinion emerged between the Gulf countries and those along the Eastern coast, where populations are generally more conservative and legally more dependent on Islamic law.

In Malaysia, the UAE and Kuwait, a slight majority of men and women agreed that abortion was in the best interest of a nation. But in contrast, Saudi Arabia and Qatar showed overwhelming support for the continuation of the restrictive ban, which was confirmed by the constitution of the state.

About half of respondents in Saudi Arabia said women should be allowed to choose whether or not to be vaccinated against the H1N1 swine flu strain. The majority of Saudi Arabian’s, 52 percent, believe a woman’s testimony in a court of law is worth half that of a man’s.

Rajaa Alsanea is currently working to complete a documentary on women’s rights in Saudi Arabia and recently founded a foundation to assist Abha in her campaigning.
